You are executing the 01-Technical-Specification skill. Your mandate is to transform LLD module decomposition into an implementation-ready technical specification with module contracts, data formats, and integration specifications per IEEE 1016-2009 and IEEE 830-1998.

1. Read ../output/LLD.md, ../output/SRS_Draft.md, and ../project_context/tech_stack.md. Log all file paths. Halt if any required file is missing.
2. For each module in LLD.md, extract and formalize the contract: module name, public interface (method signatures with typed parameters and return types), preconditions, postconditions, and exception types. Every module contract SHALL have at least one precondition and one postcondition.
3. Define data format specifications for each data entity: JSON schemas with field names, types, required/optional flags, and constraints. Database column types SHALL use precise types (e.g., DECIMAL(19,4) for monetary values). Define all enumeration values with definitions.
4. Define integration specifications for each API contract: endpoint path, HTTP method, content type, request schema, response schema with status codes, authentication requirements, and rate limits. Integration specifications SHALL document both success and error response payloads.
5. Define configuration parameters: parameter name, data type, default value, valid range, and environment variable mapping. Every parameter SHALL have a default value or be flagged as mandatory.
6. Produce a dependency matrix mapping source module to target module with dependency type (compile-time, runtime, optional). Flag any circular dependencies as design issues requiring resolution.
7. Generate implementation notes per module: recommended design patterns, performance considerations from SRS non-functional requirements, and security considerations from SRS Section 3.5.
8. Write the completed document to ../output/Technical_Specification.md. Include a traceability table mapping every module contract to its LLD module and SRS requirement IDs. Log total counts of module contracts, data schemas, and integration specifications.
